WEBVTT

00:00.219 --> 00:02.039
Previously on <i>Longmire</i>

00:02.159 --> 00:03.114
Ignore the polls.

00:03.662 --> 00:06.382
I do. But there are some things
I cann't ignore.

00:06.502 --> 00:08.553
You know what would help?
Dirt.

00:08.673 --> 00:12.127
You got any juicy Longmire secrets,
now would be the time to spill 'em.

00:12.247 --> 00:13.991
Where did you get those eyes?

00:14.111 --> 00:17.824
My dad and my ex-boyfriend are in
the middle of a nasty campaign fight.

00:17.944 --> 00:20.258
- And recently I found out that my mother...
- Your mother what?

00:20.378 --> 00:22.977
- I know what happened in Denver.
- No you don't.

00:23.097 --> 00:25.850
Word of your wifes' murder
won't leave this room.

00:25.970 --> 00:29.789
But I think that right now your daughter
might need you more than the county does.

00:31.861 --> 00:33.061
Your family's
been coming here

00:33.162 --> 00:34.796
every summer since the '80s,
right?

00:34.864 --> 00:36.598
The '70s, actually.
And we're here year-round now,

00:36.699 --> 00:38.433
so I can finally vote for you.

00:38.501 --> 00:40.068
We just got to get out
that vote!

00:40.136 --> 00:43.004
May I borrow the sheriff
for just a moment?

00:43.105 --> 00:44.506
Uh, what for?

00:44.607 --> 00:46.441
I think she's asking you
to dance.

00:46.509 --> 00:48.076
I'm not sure that's such a...
such a...

00:48.144 --> 00:50.245
Go on.
Come on!

00:52.000 --> 00:58.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:06.262 --> 01:07.862
All right, sheriff!

01:09.765 --> 01:12.367
Nice one, Walt.

01:13.703 --> 01:15.637
Hung me out to dry there.

01:15.705 --> 01:18.139
Price of politics.

01:18.240 --> 01:20.342
You, uh, want to dance?

01:20.443 --> 01:23.278
Two vodka tonics, ma'am.

01:23.346 --> 01:25.246
Thank you.

01:28.250 --> 01:29.851
Ruby.

01:29.952 --> 01:31.219
Ooh, thank you.
Mm-hmm.

01:31.320 --> 01:33.388
I thought maybe you got lost.

01:33.489 --> 01:35.023
That block of ice was charming,

01:35.124 --> 01:36.491
but it's not a very efficient
way to make a drink.

01:37.593 --> 01:38.893
Look at Ferg.

01:38.995 --> 01:41.296
Ooh, light on his feet.

01:41.397 --> 01:43.298
You go, boy!

02:15.431 --> 02:19.668
I have been asked to say a few
words about tomorrow's election.

02:19.769 --> 02:24.072
We have all grown accustomed to
the modern drumbeat for change.

02:24.173 --> 02:27.342
Our opponent seems particularly
fond of the word.

02:27.410 --> 02:30.578
And while I believe
that change can be good,

02:30.680 --> 02:34.182
I do think people too often
underestimate the value

02:34.283 --> 02:36.117
of things that never change.

02:38.788 --> 02:42.957
My friend Walt
is one of those things.

02:46.462 --> 02:49.264
Who would ask him to change
his loyalty,

02:49.365 --> 02:51.533
his honesty,

02:51.634 --> 02:53.935
his intelligence,
and compassion?

02:54.003 --> 02:55.870
Not me.

02:55.971 --> 02:57.305
Though some of us <i>do</i> think

02:57.373 --> 02:58.973
that maybe it is time
he got a cellphone.

03:00.176 --> 03:04.245
But other than that, sheriff.

03:04.346 --> 03:05.313
Speech!

03:05.414 --> 03:08.283
Speech!

03:20.996 --> 03:23.098
Thataboy, Walt!

03:24.834 --> 03:25.767
Uh...

03:25.835 --> 03:27.268
Okay?

03:28.604 --> 03:32.540
Uh...

03:36.078 --> 03:38.646
Thanks.

03:52.094 --> 03:55.997
Walt, come on.
That's not necessary.

03:56.098 --> 03:58.299
I'll get that in the morning.

03:58.367 --> 04:01.503
Doesn't seem right to leave you
with a mess.

04:01.570 --> 04:05.273
Who said anything
about you leaving?

04:05.374 --> 04:07.108
Hmm?

04:27.730 --> 04:29.864
I'm sorry. I...

04:29.932 --> 04:32.367
I got a big day.

04:32.468 --> 04:34.302
Yeah, got to get your rest.

04:34.403 --> 04:36.237
Right.

04:36.305 --> 04:38.640
I, uh... yeah.

05:09.128 --> 05:12.487
<font color="#00ffff">Longmire 02x10</font>
<font color=#00ff00>Election Day</font>
